In Java, an ArrayList is part of the java.util package and implements the List interface. Think of it as a "growable array." Unlike standard arrays which have a fixed length, an ArrayList automatically expands its capacity as you add elements.
Core Characteristics
●	Dynamic Resizing: It uses an internal array that grows by roughly 50% when it runs out of space.
●	Ordered: It maintains the insertion order of elements.
●	Index-Based: It allows random access to elements using an index, making get(index) very fast ($O(1)$).
●	Non-Synchronized: It is not thread-safe by default (unlike Vector).
●	Allows Nulls: You can store null values and duplicate elements.
